<Time>1531022398892<//Time><Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
Eunice is amazing. My hair was completely discolored and messed up from store-bought-self-colored-gray-coverage hair coloring attempts. She fixed it and knew exactly what color to recommend & apply on me to look my best. Got endless compliments on how the new color really suits me, from countless people, even strangers.

The key here is that I have sensitive scalp and get a really bad rash reaction from regular dyes, therefore never can get my hair colored professionally at salons. However, she is able to provide & use a more natural dye on me, and the color lasts! Permanently.  =)

She is now my trusted go-to person for root touch ups for about a year now. She's friendly, approachable, sweet, efficient, and professional. When I'm too busy to visit her & try to color at home, the result is just not worth the time investment.

Appointment is definitely recommended. They get really busy. Appointments are all pretty on-time. I never had to wait when I show up on time.

I used to park on the main street until I found out there are plenty of parking behind the building, with convenient access from their back door.

Everyone who work there are really sweet, nice, and friendly. Interior Decor is modern and comfortable.</Review>

I asked about roaches before we signed a lease and we were told they haven't had a single complaint-we've had roaches in our unit since day two (we clean every other day, and there's never any open containers or food sitting out - the first reaction is to always blame the tenant but obviously multiple people are having this issue), everywhere from the living room to the bathrooms to the bedroom. We've notified management and they said they would take care of it, and nothing.  Its so hard to get a hold of the staff over the phone, I have to call so many times over a period of a few days in order to even get someone to answer. Lastly, the staff in the office rotates so frequently, we hardly recognize faces for longer than a couple months. We are breaking our lease and moving. It's not worth paying what we're paying in rent to live around a neighbor who makes us hesitant to even be around him and to not only put up with the filth both inside and outside the complex, but to also put up with staff who makes you feel like they just brush off your complaint. We've been asking when the back pool will be opened, for moths we've hear "in a couple weeks." In the meantime, the front pool is getting so overcrowded we can rarely enjoy it. Same thing with the gym, we've been told it's close to opening and seems like it never does. On top of it, when talking with the staff regarding why we're breaking our lease we still have to pay the fee to terminate it regardless of the problems we've had with the complex and our neighbor...but whatever we can do to get ourselves out of here we will so I guess we're at a loss on that one.</text>

<Text>Can‚Äôt describe but here is a shot: 1.  NOT hand made. The outer shell on the spinach dumpling was store bought and freezer burnt. 2. Shrimp Dumpling...also out of a bag. 3.  Vegetable spring roll is full of ‚Äúhaiku sai‚Äù or white lettuce roots. We found one carrot string in the 3 rolls.

0x80e9139d69a1dde3:0x902dcbf2f6f6c6ac</Gmap_id>
</record></dataset><record>
< Pics>
None</Pics>
< Review>
I feel so bad having to say this, but the food here is for the most part either simply disappointing or awful. My wife is more forgiving because being Chinese she enjoyed chatting with the server who was friendly enough.

The dishes are uniformly over priced and in terms of taste, the vast majority taste like they came from the freezer. Portions on certain dishes are comically small: the gailan (Chinese broccoli) looked great in the menu photo, but was a mere few pieces, mostly random cuttings in reality. The Xialong Bao (pork soup dumplings) are at any other place served in portions of eight to ten in a basket; here only four! The char siu (bbq pork) had little flavor of any sort and came poorly plated. The Char siu bao (bbq pork buns) were edible but again the pork filling wasn't flavorful. They have a dish of pork in a black bean sauce that traditionally would contain pumpkin and often some jalapenos. Here the dish was simply fatty pork bits with no real meat and a few stray black beans.

So what was good? Well, the rice porridge with pork was okay but a little too watery according to my wife. The steamed rice cakes filled with pork which are a Cantonese dish and come wrapped in lotus leaf were fine. And they have a radish cake (daikon radish) that actually was good because it wasn't dry and clearly contained real radish. The Sesame Balls that are fried with a red bean filling were pretty good, but again likely originally frozen and the Siu Mai (pork with shrimp) was passable but you will do better elsewhere.

Other reviewers have complained that the dumplings here aren't made fresh. And truthfully, most Chinese dumpling houses do not make their own dumplings. They source them from either a few restaurants that have the resources to do so, or from companies that supply the industry or in this case, the frozen section of a grocer.  My wife and I have been told this numerous times from several restaurants in Los Angeles Chinatown and in San Francisco, including from managers. So in that note, Asie Dumpling House isn't alone.

Anyway. Staff are friendly, but many including Emily, our server, don't have great English skills but try their best. And yeah, it's over priced here.</Review>

None< /response>

We had the shrimp dumplings which were pretty good,  though the dipping sauce was not terribly tasty. Also the bean curd rolls which were awful. It appeared that they were fried but then kept warm with steam. Limp and tasteless. My friend had the ramen. Noodles and an egg in an odd broth. She didn't like it, thought it needed more flavor. The service was okay, very friendly. The bill was very cheap. We were so looking forward to a dumpling restaurant and it was less than mediocre.  It's a pretty new place, so hopefully they'll improve. We'll wait a couple of months and try again.</Review>

My surgery experience I had here over 1 year ago was exceptional, as was the overall treatment and care provided by staff. Now understand, my opinion is biased (because I also work here - going on 4 years), but here are some facts: not every interaction may be the best, but we constantly strive to better ourselves and patient customer service. If you are wanting surgery, plan for the wait, whether it‚Äôs 1 hour or 5- plan to be flexible. Any surgery (at any facility) can go longer than expected, which does indeed cause others‚Äô wait times to grow, but wouldn‚Äôt you want that extra time spent on you if you were having surgery? I can‚Äôt speak for other specialty outpatient facilities, but Regional Hand Center exceeds itself by offering emergency services to countless patients, which also delays others‚Äô wait times.. all we ask is for patience and understanding in these situations. Again, what if the tables were turned? I work the late hours, and it can be rough. BUT, at the end of the day, if you want a great outcome for your trigger finger, carpal tunnel, radius fracture or revision amputation, the wait is worth it because these surgeons definitely do it best! I work alongside all 4 of them, and am proud to represent them and this facility. Everyone has their own opinion, but take them all with stride.. < Review>
Regional Hand Center is outstanding when it comes to patient care and getting this done in a timely matter. Very knowledgeable doctors who take their time in explaining your diagnosis in detail and answering all your questions and concerns. I recommend this office to all family and friends!!!
My little brother was treated by Dr. Avena for multiple warts on multiple fingers a couple years ago. We had tried everything possible and bought everything in store shelves to try and get rid of those warts before we came to Regional Hand Center. Dr. Avena took the time to explain everything to my parents and his recommendation for treatment. We were pleased that it was extremely invasive and painless considering he was dealing with a teenager.
It only took one round of cryotherapy to get rid of all those nasty warts. They have yet to come back!!! Thank you Dr. Avena your the best!!!<//Review>

<review>Good doctor makes the difference !
I was the first time patient and I mailed in my registration paper work,  in order to save time when I got there.   The front desk staff told me:" You should bring it in with you,  not to mail it."   No body had told me over the phone that I was not supposed to mail it,  but to bring it.  However,  I didn't want to argue with her at that moment.  What will it make a difference if I mail it in, or bring it in anyway?  I think that they just don't want to open the mails and file them in time.  After I insisted that I didn't want to fill out the paperwork for the second time,  they finally went to check the mail and open the envelope for the first time.
After a short wait, I was called in for X-ray.   The staff was friendly and helpful.  Then I was put back to wait for the doctor.  The doctor came and consulted my extraction request.   He examined me and found out that my referral from my general dentist,  had made a big mistake about my tooth extraction!  Can you imagine that if they pulled out three of your good teeth by mistake?!
This doctor listened to me and examined my teeth and checked the X-ray,  then he decided to pull out the right tooth,  instead of the wrong tooth!
The doctor was very nice, soft spoken,  encouraging and professional. The whole supposed -to -be painful extraction only lasted about 20 minutes.
Even though I went through a few terrible experiences with the previous dentist and oral surgeon's offices, my hard work and painful waiting time was finally over!
Thanks for this doctor and he really made a huge difference!<//review>< Resp>

< review>
It was absolutely terrible. Okay so I do not have any major bite or jaw issues but my teeth were just a bit overcrowded so I came here. I came here for about two years and absolutely nothing happened. Like there was little to no effect. My family and I then moved to Florida, as it would be a more convenient place for us (job, money, opportunities, etc.). Of course, we needed to find a new orthodontist and we found one. So far, (it's been 5 months) my teeth have looked so so much better in this honestly pretty short amount of time. Also I found out from my new dentist and orthodontist that the way the were putting the braces on my teeth was pretty bad for my jaw, and they didn't see how any of this could be beneficial for me. Anyway I'm glad i'm out of here  :) seriously though, this orthodontic place might be good for some crowding or minor teeth problems, but it isn't good for people (very painful too, i know braces are painful anyway but going to this place just amplified it) who actually have some problems with their bite. for your own well being do not come here unless you have minor (minor= overcrowding, slight overbite, maybe a tooth that's way too upwards but not anything else) problems that you want to fix.</review>

Also, besides their braces being the most expensive compared to the rest, they give you a cheap retainer that never even fits properly. After I had my treatment, their cheap worthless retainer did nothing to retain my teeth straight, and my teeth are crooked again!<//text>

Expedia reviewer</Name>

1600905600000< /time>
< Rating>
None</Rating>
< Text>
I love going to Asilomar. I think of it as "hotel camping;" lots of nature but no TV and the amenities are not the point. The wi-fi doesn't accommodate the kids' online games and cell phone and hot-spot reception doesn't really allow you to work efficiently from the rooms. The rooms are usually clean enough but nothing fancy. The beds are not too hard, not too soft, old, but completely fine. Healthy walk to the beach and the possibility of coyotes or wild cats hangs in the air. You will definitely come into close contact with deer. A great respite.</Text>

< Review>
A fabulous place to go, by the 17 mile drive in Monterey, right on the beach. It can be chilly, so be sure to bring warm clothes. A gorgeous lobby that was designed by Julia Morgan (William Randolph Hearst‚Äôs architect) resembles a treehouse with a HUGE stone fireplace. They keep the fire roaring with enormous logs. A fun place to play pool and go for walks along the beach. The Hearst family used to own it. Well worth checking it out!</Review>

<review>This is a beautiful conference grounds in facility situated on the ocean near a public beach that has tide pools and an area where Surfers can surf. The buildings were designed by famous architect Julia Morgan and some have a rustic feel to them. Most of the rooms do not have TVs or other amenities that you would find in a typical Hotel. You can stay here and dine in the dining hall for what is kind of an expensive fee but it's worth it since you don't have to go anywhere to get food so it's very relaxing. There is a main Lodge that has a lot of activities such as ping pong pool table and add a fireplace with chairs where you can sit and read and also a cafe and Bar. Some of the rooms have special meeting areas so if you have a family gathering and you booked a bunch of rooms together you can get also a conference room this like a giant living room where you can hang out together. The weather here isn't really like Sunny Beach weather but it's warm enough and it have a swimming pool that you can use but it's often very cold.</review>< Rate>
4< /Rate>

<pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNBQSP4BqVxlZMjNEDKKnUZDdf-Evz_IYIIMYHa=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMcGh7iVtM_G8bxvEFSAVJznNplBiQZrfppvslw=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOR1qAT7P80vQMi_nc-9JUXT2ICIhpoPL5PnIe3=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pictures><resp>None< /resp><gmap_id>0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519< /gmap_id></record>

<GmapID>0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519</GmapID>< review>
Asilomar conference center and hotel is a historic location. It is a fascinating place to hold a conference. The grounds are exquisite!  I can hear the roar of the ocean I'm at least a quarter mile away. It is now the middle of January there was a storm last night the surf is absolutely amazing and its height and turbulence.the outbuildings of which there are a number of conference meeting styled venues and various housing options have been built across different time frames from the original buildings. This is not a normal hotel. If you're looking for one of those you may want to continue  your search. Not only is this a beautiful venue but it's a place of ideas and exploration across the number of different groups who hold conferences and meetings here. My room is large and situated in the beautiful coastal area of Pacific Grove. I would heartly recommend the venue especially if you will be participating in one of the conference or meetings. You may also come and just rent a room. But don't expect a TV. There's too much life and beauty around to engage with that. I give this venue a five star rating because of its overall connection to so much beyond just a place to spend the night.< /review>

< Text>
This hotel is in absolutely beautiful place to visit. It has lovely rooms and a fantastic "social lodge". Each building also has a small lounge area. However, be aware of the room you book. Historic rooms are precisely that: historic. They are a bit beat up because they have been around for many years and are a bit small. That being said, the area is beautiful and the beach access cannot be beaten. The beach is approximately seven minutes down the main path and is positively beautiful.</Text>

<Text>This is one of the best places to stay in Monterey. A Charming walkway directly to the ocean, a fire pit by the ocean for wine socials and entertainment on the weekend. Not particularly cheap except during the weekdays, it still offers Charming touches like individual rooms in the forest area, where deer can be seen directly from your patio window! There is a Starbucks concession in the main building where you check in and that particularly added points to how I view Asilomar. The only drawback I can see are that the rooms don't contain TVs or refrigerators. Rooms do have Wi-Fi which is a plus. They offer breakfast, but at $20 a plate oh, it seems a little much so we passed on that. One thing you should do is bring an ice chest with plenty of what you want to snack on. There is a Safeway in Pacific Grove that you can stock up on what you want to put in that ice chest and it is on the main drag of Pacific Grove, short distance away. Safeway also has a Starbucks by the way so one is always close by. We have been there several times and never been disappointed. You just go just where the white sand is, stretch out and enjoy a wonderful Seabreeze. I don't think it gets much better than that!</Text>< Resp>

Rustic beauty nestled close to many convenient locations.

My wife and I enjoyed spending several nights in the Willow Inn cabin. While the wifi was a bit spotty, we didn't spend enough time indoors for it to matter as much. I would definitely have rated Asilomar five stars if the wifi was more reliable. üòÅ

The views were magnificent and the on-site Cafe was nice. During the day it was a full service coffee shop, at night it doubled as a bar!

We will definitely be coming back again!<//Review>

Highly recommended.  This is a great secluded place to host a convention. A gorgeous location right next to the beach. Fantastic to see wild deer wandering about. <Text>Beautiful location and grounds, with great social hall area.  Rooms are dated but is clean and bed/sheets were comfy.  Water pressure is not great but that's because they throttle the shower heads/faucets with water-saving modifications, which is fine for the environment.  Was here for a meeting and grounds we're functional but conference rooms are inconveniently spread out all over (good for exercise but not for getting between one site and another for concurrent sessions).  Food was fine, but not fabulous--what you might expect for an Aramark operation.  Price of rooms (w meal plan) was a.vit pricey for what you get, but it's you get the convenience of being on campus, rather than slight more unique and better rooming options in the area.  The internet/wifi connection was surprisingly HORRIBLE, often unusable at certain times.  Yes, there are a lot of conference attendees but this is supposed to be a conference center!  Expect to have to rely on tethering to your mobile service to get many things done if you need internet, or plan an internet-free holiday--can't do business or have a meeting that requires access to the internet.<//Text>< Time>

<userid>100588061614421826704<//userid><Name>A K</Name><Date>1550681710905< /Date><Rating>1<//Rating>< Text>
I am stunned to read some of these glowing reviews - these must not be from the "Shores" building where I stayed.  I was so excited about our night at Asilomar in a room with a "fireplace and balcony" in this most beautiful area of California.  The beach and surroundings are undeniably beautiful, but the room was a huge disappointment.  I realize that lodging in this area is expensive, but for the $275 that I spent I felt completely taken advantage of.  There was lots of hair in the room that did not belong to my family (clumps in the drain, on the counter tops, on the bedding).  The floors were very dusty around the edges.  The accommodations are simple and dated (which is fine) but felt dirty and old with a poorly applied coat of paint to cover the last seasons damage.  The fireplace was the best part with a nifty little bag of kindling and logs to burn.  The balcony was a run down ledge on the ground floor with a sliding door that was coming off the track.  I will never go back to Asilomar.  I would rather spend $400 and get a charming and clean room at a bed and breakfast or chain hotel.  I hope that Asilomar will invest in the quality of the accommodations because the history of the property and location can't be beat.  Until then, stay away.< /Text>

< review>
A very nice place,  my good friends had their wedding reception on the property. However, when I arrived by myself and asked for directions to our lodge; I went to the cafe to get a bite to eat. I'm diabetic and it was critical that I eat.  The woman working in cafe, didn't look up to acknowledge my presence, let alone say 'hello" or 'may I help you.' I stood there for several minutes.  I know she saw me because she looked right at me when I was waiting to ask my question at the front desk. As an African American woman, I have been subjected to subtle and overt racism throughout most of my life.  It stings at little more at so-called nice places.  Buyer be aware.  The French bakery on 68 is wonderful and provided excellent service, well worth the ride back up the hill!< /review>

< Text>
This is my second time at the Asilomar hotel and conference grounds. Two years ago the place was just average. This time it was absolutely terrible. Croton bugs on the pillows, holes in the linen, lipstick marks on the glass.... the whole place is filthy. The nature around is beautiful and giving it a star only for that. The hotel itself doesn't deserve any stars. The food is awfully overpriced and not tasty. You can go into town and get an amazing dinner for half of the price you pay at the hotel. Very disappointed.</Text>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
We just got back from this lovely refuge in Monterey. It's shocking and amusing to read the bad reviews - yes, this is not the Ritz. It's an incredible time piece that is clean, well kept AND environmentally sound. The ground protect the LAST 5% (if it's even still that) of the dunes that have been mercilessly developed. The room as simple and cozy, nice balcony, great staff, great food, great for kids. It was so awesome and simple.< /text>

< UserId.>
100145190631270904397<//UserId.>
< username>
Josh Montero<//username>
<Time>1575780165626</Time><rate>4<//rate><Text>There are plenty of challenges to being a teacher. Occasionally you get to spend a weekend at a math conference that happens to be at the beach. Asilomar is hard to rate because it is something if its own species; a resort that is meant as an actual escape, one without televisions in rooms or anything glam, high tech, or fancy. Chic, it most certainly is not, but it's also not the place anyone looking for that would come. The grounds are spread out, which is both a benefit and curse. My FitBit was happy with me, and the 13k steps it took me to walk back and forth to all my conference sessions, but nothing feels cramped, so the layout is actually nice. Though even just getting around among the main social lodge, dining hall, and lodging buildings can become a lot of walking. Somehow it felt as if I were trapped in an MC Escher piece because almost everywhere you go seems to be uphill. I was sure at one point I turned around and should have been going downhill and that was still an incline. Though that aside, being away from town and able to smell the trees and the salty ocean air, to hear the waves crashing throughout the day, the environment is exceptional. It's fairly dark though, and that is also by design. Pathways are lit, safety isn't an issue, per se, but navigating and getting around at night can take a couple days to get your bearings. All told, nice but not amazing. Definitely nothing to discourage me from returning.</Text>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>

Stayed just one night but was very impressed with the place. extremely well maintained, love the communal aspect - the large dining and meeting halls are great for meeting new people. the walk to the beach is on these tidy wooden walkways (keep the dunes pristine!). The room I stayed in had two queen size beds. The bathroom was clean and there were plenty of towels and included shampoo, conditioner and lotion. Not cheap, but once you're there, relaxation is guaranteed!< /text>

<Name>Brian Garwood<//Name><Date>1535240449555<//Date>< gmap_id>
0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519< /gmap_id>
<UserId.>109869660444754220268< /UserId.></record>
</dataset><record>
< review>
Can't really beat the location. Walk to the state beach from the hotel grounds. Cottages. Our cottage had a common area with fireplace and chairs and tables, and some family board games. No ice machine in the cottage, had to walk to Phoebe's cafe to get ice (3 minute walk, about 300 steps). No microwave or fridge in the rooms, and no TV (which is great). Family atmosphere in the evenings at the main building (where you check-in and where the Phoebe's cafe is), people gathered around the big fireplace playing board games and pool. There is a also an old piano there if you want to play gently. The Crocker dining hall meal prices are absurdly high, though. So if you have a car the town has plenty of dining options. Nearby restaurants are about mike away so you can take a nice walk even if you do not have a car. They also have some bicycles to rent. Overall, great retreat place.<//review>

<Review>This is a great place to stay if you keep a few things in mind.1.This is a conference center and a CA state park. Conditions are more primitive, with dated furnishings and a bit of a walk to your room door.2.Yes, it is more expensive than one would expect, but this is CA -everything is expensive. Realize where you are! This is one of the most beautiful, unspoiled stretches of beach in the world!! The Inn at Spanish Bay is just down the coast, and their starting charge was almost 5 times what I spent for my night here.3. You may be tempted to rush out and do the tourist things -Monterey Bay Aquarium, the art galleries in Carmel, but take the time to enjoy where you are. Walk around the complex and enjoy the unique architecture. Walk on the boardwalk and look at the flowers. Walk on the beach and let the peace fill you soul.</Review>< response>

The pool is heated and There are towels available there for people who wish to use them.  They have a restaurant on the grounds which serves breakfast lunch and dinner. However we felt the prices were too high. we ate at local restaurants in Pacific Grove and found the prices there to be one half to two-thirds of what we found at the resort.  There was some deferred maintenance here but I guess that's to be expected since the property is over 100 years old. when we mentioned these items to the staff they did seem concerned so hopefully they will be addressed. The rooms aren't anything fancy but they were comfortable so we would stay here again.</Review>< Pictures>

<user>105216550081134672432</user><date>1545657742168<//date><GmapID>0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519< /GmapID>< Rating>

< user_name>
Greg Roderick<//user_name>
< pictures>
None<//pictures>
< Review>
This is a pretty unique place.  It started out as a YWCA facility in the early 1900s.  This is why it has a Boy/Girl Scout campus compound feel to it.  Many different buildings with fairly basic bedrooms and a shared common gathering place in each building.  There is the main lobby where larger groups can gather and there are conference rooms too for even bigger crowds.  What makes this place a standout, is its general setting and its location.  You feel like you're at a retreat at an exclusive location, which is why it's appealing to stay here.  If you want high end accomodations, this is not the place for you.  It's a historic facility to get away from it all, even though there's world class golfing, Cannery Row in Monterey and downtown Pacific Grove only a few miles away.  Like I said, pretty unique.</Review>

<pictures>None</pictures>< name>
Michelle C. Torres-Grant< /name>
<time>1534687902335<//time><Rate>3<//Rate>< Resp>
None</Resp>
< Text>
The best thing about this conference site is it's setting on a gorgeous stretch of coastline. There's a network of walking trails among the dunes and water's edge which have been rehabilitated with California native plants. The design of the buildings and grounds is very nice, but a bit run down. Almost everything could use some renovations. WiFi is super duper slow. I find that unacceptable these days for a conference venue that caters to many business and industry events. If you really need to get things done online you will get it done quicker and with less frustration if you drive to a nearby coffee shop in Pacific Grove. The food at Asilomar is decent, but way overpriced. You can find many great eateries nearby for far less than you'll spend for an Asilomar meal ticket.</Text>

<user>111758958759885743168<//user>< pictures>
None< /pictures>
<gmapID>0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519</gmapID>< Text>
Two stars means "just ok", so here are my thoughts about my stay.

Stayed there 10/1/19 through 10/4/19 in the "Lodge" building, room 208. If you value hearing the ocean and sounds of nature from your room, do not stay in this room! An ancient water heater is located directly beneath the room and the thing goes off roughly every 15 minutes. One of the facility workers told us it is to be replaced, at some point. It was super annoying and I was willing and able to move to another room, but my friend convinced me it was too much trouble and the view of the ocean was more important to her. Luckily I brought ear plugs with me so I didn't have to hear it overnight. And, we were out and about during the day.

I've read other complaints about the appearance of the grounds/landscaping. Really, there is no landscaping. The dirt areas are natural, with fallen trees and dead plants in their various forms of growth and decay. I found the same at Pt. Lobos where many downed trees lay where they've fallen, only cleared from roads and paths. I understand the reason for this, so although it was a tad shocking at first, I got used to it. The area has been suffering with a drought and strong, blustery winter storms (so a park volunteer explained to me).

As for the cafeteria, the meal tickets are expensive, imo, and the the choices limited. The frittata was pretty bad on the one morning we went. I think any meat options are scarce for any variety of reasons.

It is beautiful and historic, so do stay there. Just be aware that some of the buildings are very old and in need of updating. I think there's only so much they can do with redwood paneling that has been abused through the decades.<//Text>

<Text>Instead of a Julia Morgan experience, I got a white-walled, 80's renovated and dilapidated Motel 6 experience (Pirates Den).  Very disappointing.  Room smelled musty and a/c didn't work. Light bulb is LED equivalent to maybe 120W which are way too bright to be practical.

<user>105670622787945901627<//user>< Name>
William Nugent< /Name>
<Time>1568840229617< /Time>< rating>
3< /rating>
< review>
I was told this facility is a state park, run by a for-profit company. We were in a guest building on the property line furthest from the ocean. We were part of a group booking but for some reason we were not housed with the rest of our group. The room was dark and the light fixtures didn't help. No TV in room, adequate WIFI, twin beds and an "earthy" smell in the room. I only saw one outlet available for guest use (without moving furniture) which was on the wall next to the side of a bed; the plug kept falling out of the socket. The wall sconce switch between the beds was loose and looked as if it had been replaced several times with non OEM parts. The furniture looks like it was purchased in the '60's or '70's. Beds were comfortable, linen fresh.

The bathroom is clearly dated. The shower had good water pressure, but the head was low and there was mineral buildup that needed to be cleaned; the bathtub was small. Towels were fresh. Bring your own bottled water as none is provided.The sliding glass door was difficult to open, a fold up security bar, centered horizontally locked the door. The latch on the handle didn't function properly and the guides on the track need adjustment. There is a plastic table and chairs on the balcony. No glassware,  only individually wrapped plastic cups. No in room refrigerator, microwave, coffee or tea service.

Meal service is institutional type cooking, in a main dining hall, set meal times, with vouchers presented at entry. Usually two or three meal choices per meal, large portions with desserts and coffee, tea and water included. Wine is available,  however I believe it's at your expense. You won't go hungry but check ahead if you have diet restrictions like gluten-free, vegan, etc.

I didn have any direct interaction with the staff, however if we passed each other I was warmly greeted.< /review>

< text>
These grounds may have mediocre wifi and limited food, however the connection the hotel rooms have with the pine forests and dunes is beautiful beyond words! This has been the favorite hotel I've ever stayed at, compared to even standard 4-star hotels. The connection to Nature you get from staying in Asilomar is very unique and memorable, the woodpeckers fly around you, the jays and hawks call from the woods, the irises bloom during spring, and the tumble of the ocean waves is so soothing and calm at night. The loss of good wifi is well worth the connections to nature, which our tech-bombarded generations need!<//text>

<text>Beautiful surrounding and walkway but front desk not too friendly. Our room didn't have a TV or a telephone inside. The walkway to the beach is beautiful and spacious bathroom. Staff needs to be more attentive and caring.<//text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><Resp>None</Resp><gmap_id>0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519<//gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<Pictures>None<//Pictures><user_id>117721031202383665822</user_id>< Date>
1547411671148<//Date>
< Review>
My family has had a reunion here every 2 years for about 20 years. The fact that we keep coming back definitely says something. We love the option of getting a meeting room so there is a common place for the 20+ people in our group to gather. The meeting room has a fire place, and the staff will work with you to ensure you have the necessary furniture, and for an additional charge, stock it with hot beverages throughout the day. In the past all guests rooms have been centered around the meeting room, but with recent updates, rooms for larger families are located in a different part of the grounds.

The property is gorgeous and well maintained. It's a short walk to a public beach through protected sand dunes. The lobby has puzzles and boardgames to borrow, and 2 pool tables. The dining hall has always done a good job cooking for large groups of people. Not a 5 star restaurant, but better than most mass produced meals I've had. They are willing to work with dietary restrictions, and have kids meals available if you ask.

The rooms themselves are dated, but I've never gone to Asilomar to spend time in my hotel room. There are no TV's on the property, and cell service / WiFi can be spotty. But the pros far out weigh the cons.< /Review>

<Rating>1< /Rating><text>I don't know on what basis 1000 something other reviewers have given this hotel more than 4 star rating.

I stayed here for a conference, for which the hotel charged "special conference" rate of more than $200 per night, just to stick most of the guests up with rundown ill-maintained rooms with sloppy cleaning. My room's hardwood floor was blackened with years of usage and probably has never been polished or cleaned since the hotel was built. The water taps were rusty and leaking (for all the save water, save planet posters everywhere in the room, the least the hotel could do is check the leaky taps)! When I checked in the bathroom in my room had beach sand, which was not cleaned from the previous check-out probably.

The food served for breakfast, lunch, dinner was downright horrible, and often recycled from previous days' leftovers. California is one of the best places in the US to get delicious food from cuisines around the world, but this hotel probably employees caterer who should not be in the catering business ever!

The internet was so awful, it was an ordeal to just check your email. And if you wanted to escape these horrible services, any decent eating place or cafes are more than a mile walk away, so you are stuck here with this horrible service unless you take cab or drive everywhere!

Will not recommend to anyone at any cost!< /text><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< response>

0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519< /gmap_id>
< text>
Great campus with beautiful examples of craftsman architecture. Fire places are abundant, and the guest hall includes pool tables and puzzles. Stayed as part of a conference - plenty of large spaces for groups of about 200 to 300, or more. Food was included for our conference and meals were very good, including vegetarian options. We also enjoyed the small bar between meals and relaxing at the many outdoor seating areas. The surrounding grounds are gorgeous, particularly Asilomar State Beach, and only a short walk to a monarch sanctuary as well as the Pebble Beach golf course. Only downside would be the slightly dated fixtures in the rooms, but they could be forgiven for preserving a 1970s/80s classic feel. Otherwise the rooms were generally clean and in good repair.< /text>

< review>
Attended a conference there. The conference grounds are large with buildings spread throughout the campus. The buildings are a bit dated and they didn't have air conditioning during a heat wave so everyone was sweating. But the staff were very friendly and helpful and tried their best to open windows and doors and provide refreshments. Overall a very good experience.< /review>

<Time>1557540598470< /Time><Rate>1< /Rate><Review>Don't listen to the sheeple and the idiots - I know you're accustomed to entertaining their foolishness being from California and all, but, in this case, it's time to block all that out. The facts here are simple: Asilomar is pricey even for Monterey, and it is a run-down dump. If you don't care about those two elementary details, you are likely to join the rest of these cretins in blissful and complete satisfaction.

*Edit* I am going to add some specifics:

1) The carpet in our room is ratty.
2) The tile in our bathroom (the bathroom itself is tiny and immensely dated) is cracked. The grout is also enormously discolored.
3) The room is worn - trim is covered in scuff marks, wallpaper is peeling, window lining is cracked, furniture is old.
4) The decking outside the room is incredibly unsound, and appears to be suffering from dry rot.
5) We are located as far from any amenities as-offered by Asilomar as is possible.

Frankly, I couldn't be any more unsatisfied. I've seen Red Roof Inns, Econolodges, and Motel 6s that were far more well-appointed. Asilomar is a scam.</Review>< pics>

<Rating>4< /Rating>< review>
Awesome venue and lodging! A quaint retreat type place with an amazing location inside asilomar state park!  Come escape the urban jungle! Beautiful architecture designed by the renowned architect, Julia Morgan. Actually the whole site was essentially her doing. Located in a forest yet minutes walk from the beach. And only minutes drive to down town Pacific Grove , Monterey, and pebble beach.
The hotel itself it's like a Travelodge level place with simple rooms, clean but older. Some are historic with classic era furnishings and an available fire place or fireplace in a common lounge. The grounds are well kept and a beautiful place too walk around.<//review>

<review>Great place for any even close to beach ok rooms could use an update<//review><Pics>None< /Pics><Response>None<//Response>< GmapID>
0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519<//GmapID>
</record></dataset><record>
< Review>
My wife and I booked a room at Asilomar last weekend. Because we wanted a bed big enough for both of us- the room cost us $241/night. This is an outrageous price considering the outdated condition of the rooms. The room had not been updated since the 1970's. One of the bathroom doors was missing, the outer door was a pocket door that didn't close right and didn't have a lock. The small junky fridge hummed all night next to the bed and the heater was so loud it woke me up every time it kicked on. The rooms do not have a TV, no biggy. But, you would think they would offer some amenities for $241 per night?
If you want breakfast, you are required to buy a meal tix at a cost of $25/person for a cafeteria style meal. They do have a small cafe with over priced coffee. I paid $3.50 for a plain cup of coffee (starbucks is $2.10 for the same size cup) when I went to get a refill I was told it would be another $1 for the refill.

I gave Asilomar 1 star for location. But, be prepared to be disappointed with the quality of the accommodations and the high prices!</Review>

< rate>

<text>I was here for a family reunion and decided that one must stay on these famous grounds at least once in a lifetime - and that's the most I would recommend.  We managed to book a room at a last minute 'discounted' rate of $160 plus tax for a total of about $190 and it was obviously mostly for the 'experience' because the room was by far the smallest accommodation we have ever occupied, with the bathroom, closet and bedroom being about 200 square feet, thereby making it unquestionably the highest cost per square foot of any room we have hired.  The double bed, not the most uncomfortable ever but uniquely sloped to push both sleepers uncomfortably together, was squeezed between the wall and the door and there is no way they should have marketed this for two people.  The atmosphere is 'original' (as in 1910 vintage, unmodified except for the bathroom fixtures and energy efficient lamps) and the bare wood walls set the tone everywhere as well as being a major fire trap.  The next day we stayed off campus in a regular hotel room for much less money but much bigger accommodation.  Additional comments from others in our group include 'they make you pay for everything here' and 'they won't let you bring anything to eat in from the outside and you must buy everything on site' although I did find an ice machine which delivered large amounts of ice for free!  In the morning housekeeping started talking loudly outside our door at 8AM and knocked loudly on our door at 8:30.</text><pics>None</pics><resp>None</resp>< Gmap_id>

<rating>5< /rating><review>I spent the weekend here as part of a retreat. The location can not be beat. Grounds feel like a National Park lodge - basic but accommodating (no TV, one pillow, not so comfortable beds). I shared a room with a three other women and we were each able to have our own bed - definitely a plus! The room also had a fireplace with all the wood and kindling ready to light - also very enjoyable!

The main lodge had a roaring fire going at night and lots of chairs for casual conversations.

The food was good for a cafeteria style meal. It was a little pricey for a cafeteria but super convenient. Dinner did include salad, main, dessert, bread, and coffee / tea so that is probably why it was more pricey. Great gluten free options - a GF biscuit in the morning and special GF pie at night.

I will come back next year for the retreat and look forward to my stay here.<//review><Pictures>None<//Pictures><Resp>None<//Resp><Gmap_id>0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519< /Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<Text>Check-in was agonizingly slow. Not because there was a line, but because the desk attendant was apparently new and unfamiliar with the computer screens, with nobody there to help her. Room was 90 degrees, thermostat was stuck on even at coolest setting. Housekeeping promised to report it and I separately spoke directly to maintenance; NOTHING was done. I spent the rest of my stay turning furnace fan on to warm up and off to avoid roasting--so getting up in a cold room was unpleasant every morning. Maintenance was generally poor; headboard had fallen off wall and basin sink cold water valve was loose in fixture and will soon leak. At its best, this is a conference center dorm -- no TV, no in-room phones, no fridge, no in-room coffee. < Review>
I have attended a conference every 1.5 to 2 years or so at Asilomar for the past 14 years . Every visit brings updated amenities. I noticed the newly redone patio facing the meadow. Wi-Fi is in all rooms now. The catering is much improved. The Julia Morgan designed buildings are as beautiful as ever. The grounds and nearby beaches are wonderful. Deer everywhere! Raccoons are large and unafraid of humans.<//Review>

We chose this location as we were attending a wedding receiption there. The reviews were mediocre but it was an easy pick with a baby. The checkin was easy and friendly but it stopped being fun there. The drive to the parking lot was far and then when we got there, we had to walk a ways to the room. <text>I attended a scientific conference at Asilomar. As someone who has attended several conferences at a variety of hotels, Asilomar was a lackluster venue. My biggest complaint is that the wifi was very weak, in both our rooms and in the main conference Hall. This made it extremely difficult to do work, which was ostensibly the purpose of the trip. The food was also just fine. There were limited options- it felt much more like a college dining hall than a grown up conference venue. The view at Asilomar was great, however. Unfortunately, the nearest beach was experiencing a bloom of kelp flies that covered the sand in a carpet making the beach difficult to enjoy. Overall Asilomar was adequate but would not rank in my top percent of conference venues.</text>< pics>

<userid>118047535639301721666<//userid>< Name>
Zachary Fellows</Name>
<time>1540150331576<//time>< rate>
2</rate>
<text>The punch line is this is a geographically gorgeous place, but the "hotel" aspect is a huge letdown and left us feeling ripped off by offering an overpriced experience that does not compete with even the most budget class of motels.

The rooms are clustered into lodges that are reminiscent of summer camp cabins. On the outside, they fit in nicely with the surrounding scenery and are quite pretty - bonus is you can walk to the nearby beach in minutes. On the inside, these are 1960-70s-era rooms that don't appear to have been updated in decades, down to the butter yellow color scheme that permiated the room. Our room was large, but was furniture was scarce leaving it to feel very empty. Most the wood furniture was falling apart. Screens over the windows were warped so much you could fit your hand through the gap they left. Stains marked the curtains, carpet noticably.

I'd expect this if I was going to summer camp and staying in a cabin, not paying $200 a night for a "hotel". Other very noticeable missing features: our room had no TV, coffee maker, microwave, fridge, or even a phone (phone was in the hallway outside). We later learned you can "rent" a fridge from the front desk at something like $10 a night. Some of our friends note their room was upgraded - still without a TV, but theirs had a Keurig stocked only with decaf. It seems your mileage may vary on whether your room is upgraded or not. Others on here have mentioned incorrect or double billing at what seems like an alarming frequency, but that hasn't happened to us as of yet.

Ultimately, I would come for the scenery that this facility happens to be existing in, but the basic execution of the hotel aspect is embarrassingly bad.< /text><pics>None< /pics>< response>
None</response>

< review>
The accomodations need to be updated but the grounds, the main lodge and the boardwalk above the mighty Pacific are stunning. They've spent the money on the grounds and the common areas. Asilomar is a state park so there isn't unlimited cash to update all of the rooms, of which there are many and from different time periods. The original accomodations were designed by Julia Morgan. Other buildings were added in the 70's, 80's and 90's.
WiFi is sketchy. Best to leave your devices at home and plug into the mighty Pacific instead.<//review>

<Text>We were looking forward to our trip and staying at this beautiful property only to be put in the furthest building on the property behind HR and next to facilities not even near the main entrance and had to park on the city street because there was not a parking lot for our building (woodside). I arrived at check in right at 4:00 so cant see it being a case of no other rooms being available. The building we were in was very old and dirty. There were visible stains on the carpets and there was a 2 inch gap under our front door so spiders came in our room. We were also the only ones in our building until around 8:30 when another group arrived. We arent snobby, high maintenance people and knew it was a historic hotel and saw what the photos looked like online but in person they did not look like this. Maybe its just the woodside building which adds to our feeling that we were shooed off to this building because we had a preschooler with us or because we got a large discount on the night through travelocity. I really, really wanted to love asilomar but am just left dissapointed.</Text>< Pics>

Asilomar is ok.

<Rate>2<//Rate>< Review>
When planning our 25th anniversary I wanted to make the occasion something special for my wife and I. My parents were so excited to hear the next generation was going to enjoy Asilomar again. I am sad to say that the experience was not what we expected.
‚Ä¢	We were booked into the wrong room. This despite calling the 888 number twice stating that ours was a special occasion ‚Äì our 25th anniversary. Regardless, we were booked into a tiny room with two tiny twin beds. This despite the fact that I am 6‚Äô5‚Äù! Prior to being assigned this room we were assigned one with four beds! I made it quite clear that it was just my wife and I.
‚Ä¢	Upon our arrival we were checked-in by Mia. She made no mention of our special occasion. Initially I was stunned by her lack of attention to this important detail, the whole reason for our stay! My wife and I felt insulted and humiliated though we said nothing at the time.
‚Ä¢	The room we were assigned had no ability to cool the room, there was no AC. The room became uncomfortably hot our 2nd night, I was almost sweating. At 2:00am I went to the Front Desk to complain. Feeling frustrated and upset, I really unloaded on her. I told her everything in this letter. She was very sweet and compassionate. She gave us a fan. Being Monterey, it did not surprise me that there was no AC. What was surprising was that there was no way to securely leave the sliding glass door open while sleeping or away. What prevented this was a folding security bar that, when in position, prevented the sliding glass door from opening at all. We did not feel safe in a room at street level with nothing preventing entry to our room via the balcony, if the sliding glass door was unlocked. Maybe more importantly, we did not see a single security person anywhere on the property during our three-day stay. I found this to be un-settling considering all the random acts of violence that occur almost daily in the United States.
‚Ä¢	The lock/latch on our sliding door also did not work. The only way it could be locked was using the folding bar.
In summary, we were very disappointed with our stay for the reasons stated. I very much want to see the Asilomar succeed for generations to come. I look forward to bringing our daughter one day. It is my hope that you will bring Asilomar back up to par with what it used to be, and on par with today‚Äôs other fine hotels.< /Review>

<Text>The location of this place is beautiful and breathtaking! It is right by the ocean and sunsets are gorgeous. The food was really delicious and the chef tried to have a diverse menu which was different each night. This is an ideal place for a retreat or scientific merting. The only negative point are the rooms. the rooms look like they have not been updated since the 1980. They have a nice cabin feel. If you are looking for a retreat disconnected from the outside world, this is the destination. But if you are looking place to do someoffice work, it maybe challenging. <gmapID>0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519< /gmapID><Date>1516667449774</Date>< text>
Joke with the family that Asilomar is lazy camping. It's a hotel in the Monterey area but it's also a state park.

Day one, check into room, visit beach, walk around facility. Dinner in Monterey, aquarium at night, then back to lodge to play pool and board games.

Day 2 swim in heated pool, cruise the beach trails, shopping in town, aquarium, dinner out then back to hotel by 7 to sit around outside camp fire pit and roast marshmallows.

There is no TV in rooms, but as a parent we don't travel anywhere without a laptop or tablet or both. The wifi is strong and easily streamed movies of Netflix.

My teens favorite aspect was the beds. Queen plus three twins. My daughter didn't need to share a bed with her younger, wiggly siblings.<//text>

< rating>
4</rating>
<review>We stayed here for two nights while exploring the northern end of Big Sur. The price was a bit more moderate than anything IN Big Sur, but still a bit high for such basic accommodation.

That said, we loved it! It felt a bit like adult summer camp with hotel-style lodges and rooms set in a forested area within walking distance of the beach. Campfires were lit up around the property, but, unfortunately for us, they were all private fires for groups staying on the grounds. We paid a bit extra for a balcony and wished we could have spent more time out there, just enjoying the trees. (Actually, a coffeepot in the room would have been great. And if you care, there was no TV.)

The biggest downfall was the poor sound proofing. We could hear EVERYTHING the people in the next room said. Also, at 6 am one of the mornings, I heard a knock at the door and someone started keying into our room. I leapt out of bed, only to discover it was not our room. It sounded so close, I could have sworn it was.

Recommended!</review>< name>
Jennifer Lund<//name>

< Name>

<gmap_id>0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519< /gmap_id><text>For several years we have driven by the Asilomar Conference Grounds during our vacations to the Monterey Bay Area.  We finally decided to book a trip to stay at the property.  We booked 3 nights and upon check in, found that we were in a non ocean view room and asked if there were ocean view rooms available.  The woman checking me in said yes and it was a $40 per night upgrade.  I said yes and as she was finishing checking me in the employee next to her was checking someone else in and that person also wanted an upgraded ocean view room and was quoted only $22 per night.  So, essentially, I paid $54 more because I checked in with a different person.

When I arrived at the building where our room was, we could see the ocean at a distance, much further away from the water than I was led to believe.  I quickly realized we would not be enjoying our view.  You could not see the ocean unless you were in the bed (the sitting area in the room had no view).  The building is designed with the walkway passing in front of each room.  So anyone walking to and from their rooms can look directly in to any room with the curtains open.  Now imagine you are laying in bed (the only place in the room where you can see the ocean) and every other guest that walks by makes eye contact with you.  A little creepy.  Needless to say, we kept our blinds closed most of the trip.

I was also a little dismayed that there are no land line phones in the room, so you better have a cell carrier with coverage.  Also, there are no Televisions in the room.  Final complaint....coffee.  There is not a coffee maker in the room, which means for a morning cup of coffee you have to drive to the main building and pay $2 for a simple cup of coffee each morning.

My vision for this trip with my wife is to lounge around the room with an ocean view....waking up in the morning and enjoying a cup of coffee in bed with a beautiful view.  Instead, we had to wake up, drive to the main building and buy coffee, and then sit in a room with the blinds closed so people were not staring at us as they walked by.

Lesson learned and romantic vacation ruined.</text><Resp>None</Resp><userid>112763982955886412314<//userid><Pictures>None</Pictures><time>1397584316050<//time>< rate>

<time>1502944288738<//time><rating>4< /rating>< review>
The cafe and store in the center aren't very good with overly priced food for average and even poor food. The smores kit is extremely overpriced and the firepit is complicated and not particularly well explained. The hotel itself is nice if basic and there is a limit to plug sockets but you can get around it. The beds are wierdly arranged as well. There is a short walk to the beach and it is incredible with alright views, extremely soft sand and an ice cold sea. There is a swimming pool but it is a long walk from the hotels at the far end. The placement of this hotel is brilliant, a short drive (or a medium length walk) from Monterey and the incredible aquarium. Overall we could and should of stayed in Monterey longer and the hotel was up to standards</review>

<user_name>Orville Chomer< /user_name>< Time>
1391741098916</Time>
< rate>
4< /rate>
<text>If you are expecting some posh lodging and/or high-end dining experience... you've come to the wrong place. This is [not] what this place is about.

This place is basically a nice high-end camp. Its not as nice as a nice hotel, but its nicer than any camp I've ever been to. Meals are pre-set both in selection and time you can eat them in the dining hall, the food is very good though.

There is no phone or television in your room but this is by design. You're supposed to be getting away from it all after all!  There is wifi... it is a little ify but better than some I've seen at some hotels. Cellular coverage on my AT&T phone seems to be pretty good too.

There are deer running around all over the place (which is pretty cool). The beach on the ocean is within walking distance (also nice).

The bad part: The front desk. ..
- Get there early? Want to have your luggage put behind the desk so that your not stuck in the lobby waiting for your room to get ready? Tough.
- Want to book a room for an extra night at the front desk. Tough. You have to go to their web site to do it.

The way the front desk is run is abysmal. Otherwise the place is very nice.</text>< Pics>
None<//Pics>
< resp>
None<//resp>

< rating>
3< /rating>
< username>
John K Nelson</username>
< Date>
1458684052581<//Date>
< pictures>
None</pictures>
<response>None</response><Text>We have had many enjoyable stays at Asilomar over the years, so revisiting after a pause of eight years had the potential to start a new chapter in our relationship with this place.  Unfortunately, a number of factors weighed heavily on our experience.  First, whereas we always stayed within the main compound, this time we were put in a room across the road.  We could still hear the ocean, but traffic on the access road (Asilomar Ave.) was audible.  The room was clean and tidy but quite worn down, with sliding doors not fitting properly, faucets/shower/toilet never updated (which is odd considering the need to conserve water in this area), and no coffee-maker, cups or etc. as amenities in a room that, with a senior discount, cost around $150 per night.  No breakfast included, although one could purchase full fare at $18 per person, or go to the cafe next to the front desk.  One of our biggest disappointments was the decline of the Monterey pine grove due to pitch canker disease.  Trees are suffering and are left to fall of their own accord, and so look quite pathetic on the way down.  Several large trees that had collapsed over by the swimming pool were especially skeletal and sad to see.  While it's admirable the resort is replanting these trees, it'll take decades before they are even half the size of the originals.  On the two days in mid-March 2016 we were there (Thurs. and Fri.) the nearby Asilomar beach smelled like decaying organic material...so much so I thought a whale had gotten trapped in underwater rocks and was rotting away.  Wanting a nice beach to stroll along, we went to Carmel's famous Sunset beach.  While pleasant, we found it overrun with dogs off leash, having a great time at the expense of folks like us who just wanted to experience the surf without barking and dog scuffles.  Like any review, these opinions are subjective and so readers can ignore them and experience Asilomar on their own.  For a conference, it might still be great, but for casual visitors, there needs to be concerted attention to upgrading and enhancing the experience of spending a couple nights.< /Text><gmap_id>0x808de1301ce496cb:0x763d96cf8eb0e519</gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
